early investments in maternal education as a driver for eliminating female circumcision evidence from egypt chp pcor freeman spogli institute for international studies center for health policy center for primary care and outcomes research stanford university fsi centers & programs research centers center on democracy development and the rule of law center for international security and cooperation center on food security and the environment stanford health policy the europe center walter h shorenstein asia pacific research center research programs program on energy and sustainable development rural education action program educational programs stanford program on international and cross cultural education inter university center for japanese language studies ford dorsey program in international policy studies affiliated programs center for innovation in global health research programs & projects by topic by expert by geographic area publications featured publications by author by topic by geographic area people directory chp pcor experts guide events upcoming recent with papers podcasts & video news recent opinion around the web about us chp pcor history annual report map & directions contact us about fsi support fsi quick links department of medicine school of medicine fellowships and funding opportunities cdeha request for seed project proposals cadma request for proposals scholarly concentration in health services & policy research rosenkranz prize for health care research in developing countries follow us on twitter events send by email share online share on facebook share on twitter share on google early investments in maternal education as a driver for eliminating female circumcision evidence from egypt research in progress seminar date and time february 29 2012 1 30 pm 3 00 pm availability open to the public no rsvp required speakers jenny liu sepideh modrek phd please note all research in progress seminars are off the record any information about methodology and or results are embargoed until publication there has been a dramatic decline in female circumcision in egypt in recent decades fewer than 40 of girls born in the mid 1990s are circumcised by age 13 compared to nearly 90 of girls born in the 1980s and the proportion continues to decline we examine the role of maternal education as a key driver of this change using information from five waves of the egypt demographic health surveys 1992 2008 we confirm a strong association between maternal education and the likelihood that daughters aged 8 18 are circumcised when we apply a fixed effects instrumental variables estimation procedure that exploits differences in the historical rise in women1s educational attainment across areas our results show that mothers who completed primary school are 59 percentage points less likely to circumcise their daughter this estimate is about seven times larger than the ols fixed effects estimate suggesting that the true effect of maternal education on daughters1 circumcision likelihood is much higher than previously reported the historical rapid increase in women1s education in egypt can be linked to education policies enacted a generation ago and female circumcision may be one example where early investments into women1s education can have considerable impacts on the future path of cultural change location msob x303 medical school office building room x303 1265 welch road stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact christine geibel parent research projects stanford health policy research in progress seminars series topics egypt search chp search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages events of interest tba kristiansen ivar kristiansen md phd mph the cost effectiveness of osteoporosis treatment in high risk osteoporotic women hau liu kaleb d michaud reference based pricing past present and future jennifer schneider dena m bravata hau liu vaccinate early and often health benefits and costs of pandemic response strategies for pandemic h1n1 2009 and influenza a h5n1 or avian flu douglas k owens alan m garber david hutton nayer khazeni support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 736 0815 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
